%N A013661 Decimal expansion of Pi^2/6 = zeta(2) = Sum_{m>=1} 1/m^2.
%C A013661 "In 1736 he [Leonard Euler, 1707-1783] discovered the limit to the infinite series, Sum 1/n^2. He did it by doing some rather ingenious mathematics using trigonometric functions that proved the series summed to exactly Pi^2/6. How can this be? ... This demonstrates one of the most startling characteristics of mathematics - the interconnectedness of, seemingly, unrelated ideas." - Clawson [See Hardy and Wright, Theorems 332 and 333. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Jan 20 2017]
%C A013661 Also dilogarithm(1). - _Rick L. Shepherd_, Jul 21 2004
%C A013661 Also Integral_{x>=0} x/(exp(x)-1) dx. [Abramowitz-Stegun, 23.2.7., for s=2, p. 807]
%C A013661 For the partial sums see the fractional sequence A007406/A007407.
%C A013661 Pi^2/6 is also the length of the circumference of a circle whose diameter equals the ratio of volume of an ellipsoid to the circumscribed cuboid. Pi^2/6 is also the length of the circumference of a circle whose diameter equals the ratio of surface area of a sphere to the circumscribed cube. - _Omar E. Pol_, Oct 07 2011
%C A013661 1 < n^2/(eulerphi(n)*sigma(n)) < zeta(2) for n > 1. - _Arkadiusz Wesolowski_, Sep 04 2012
%C A013661 Volume of a sphere inscribed in a cube of volume Pi. More generally, Pi^x/6 is the volume of an ellipsoid inscribed in a cuboid of volume Pi^(x-1). - _Omar E. Pol_, Feb 17 2016
%C A013661 Surface area of a sphere inscribed in a cube of surface area Pi. More generally, Pi^x/6 is the surface area of a sphere inscribed in a cube of surface area Pi^(x-1). - _Omar E. Pol_, Feb 19 2016
%C A013661 zeta(2)+1 is a weighted average of the integers, n > 2, using zeta(n)-1 as the weights for each n. We have: Sum_{n >= 2} (zeta(n)-1) = 1 and Sum_{n >= 2} n*(zeta(n)-1) = zeta(2)+1. - _Richard R. Forberg_, Jul 14 2016
%C A013661 zeta(2) is the expected value of sigma(n)/n. - _Charlie Neder_, Oct 22 2018
%C A013661 Graham shows that a rational number x can be expressed as a finite sum of reciprocals of distinct squares if and only if x is in [0, Pi^2/6-1) U [1, Pi^2/6). See section 4 for other results and Theorem 5 for the underlying principle. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Aug 04 2020
%C A013661 From _Peter Bala_, Aug 24 2025: (Start)
%C A013661 By definition, zeta(2) = lim_{n -> oo} s(n), where s(n) = Sum_{k = 1..n} 1/k^2. The convergence is slow. For example, s(50) = 1.6(25...) is only correct to 1 decimal digit.
%C A013661 Let S(n) = Sum_{k = 0..n} (-1)^(n+k)*binomial(n, k)*binomial(n+k, k)*s(n+k). It appears that S(n) converges to zeta(2) much more rapidly. For example, S(50) = 1.64493406684822643647241516664602(137...) gives zeta(2) correct to 32 decimal digits. Cf. A073004. (End)
